ranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Payen","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["French: from the Old French personal name <i>Pagen</i>, <i>Paien</i>, from Latin <i>Paganus</i>, from <i>paganus</i> ‘country-dweller’, a derivative of <i>pagus</i> ‘of or relating to the countryside’, possibly given to a child not yet baptized (because of its later sense of ‘pagan, heathen’). Alternatively, a nickname for a country-born person. This surname is also found in the West Indies (mainly Haiti) and Mauritius.","English: variant of   Payne  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Payan","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Jose, Manuel, Ramon, Carlos, Jesus, Leticia, Luis, Ana, Cruz, Juana, Roberto, Rodolfo.","Spanish (<b>Payán</b>): perhaps from Mozarab <i>päiên</i> ‘cave, ravine’, from Hispanic Latin <i>pedia</i>, derived from <i>pedem</i> ‘foot’. In Spain, this surname is found mainly in Andalusia.","French: Occitan variant of   Payen  ."]},{"name":"Pesnell","meanings":["Probably an altered form of French (Normandy) <b>Pesnel</b>: from a vernacular pet form of the old personal name   Payen  , or a topographic name for someone who lived by a fence or palissade, from a shortened form of <i>paissenel</i>, <i>pessenel</i>, a diminutive of <i>paisson</i>, <i>pesson</i> ‘post, stake’. This surname was brought to North America from England."]},{"name":"Pean","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Georges, Michel, Colette, Fabienne, Herve, Jacques, Maryse, Pierre.","French (<b>Péan</b>): regional variant of   Payen  .","Breton (<b>Péan</b>): cognate of French   Payen  ."]},{"name":"Payne","meanings":["English: from the Middle English and Old French personal name <i>Pai(e)n</i>, <i>Pagen</i> (from Latin <i>Paganus</i>), a fairly common personal name among Normans. It derived from a word that originally meant ‘villager, rustic’, later ‘heathen’, but it had doubtless lost these connotations in its use as a late medieval personal name. This name has also been established in Ireland since the 14th century.","History: Thomas Payne, who was a freeman of Plymouth Colony in 1639, was the founder of a large American family, which included Robert Treat Paine (1731–1814), one of the signers of the Declaration of Independence. See also   Paine  ."]}]},{"name":"Thomas","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["New Testament name, borne by one of Christ's twelve apostles, referred to as ‘Thomas, called Didymus’ (John 11:16; 20:24). <i>Didymos</i> is the Greek word for ‘twin’, and the name is the Greek form of an Aramaic byname meaning ‘twin’. The given name has always been popular throughout Christendom, in part because St Thomas's doubts have made him seem a very human character."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Sir Thomas de Payen I - Count of Gisfors was born before 1136, in Market Bosworth, Leicestershire, England, his father, Hugues II de Payens 1st Grand Master of the Knights Templar, was 65 and his mother, Catherine Sinclair, was 26. He had at least 1 son with Lady Elizabeth de Thoms. He died in 1189, in Market Bosworth, Leicestershire, England, United Kingdom."},"et":{"before 1136–1189":"enne 1136–1189","1129–Male":"1129–Surnud","1136–1189":"1136–1189","1125–Female":"1125–Surnud","1170–1245":"1170–1245","1070–1136":"1070–1136","1109–1171":"1109–1171","1129":"1129","before 1136":"enne 1136","24 May 1136":"24. mai 1136","1125":"1125","1136":"1136","1245":"1245","1189":"1189"